{"title_page": "Whitney MacMillan", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Whitney MacMillan\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1929|9|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Orono, Minnesota]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|11|1929|9|25}}\n| death_place = [[Vero Beach, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = Minneapolis, Minnesota\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Yale University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman<br/>Philanthropist\n| title = CEO of [[Cargill]]\n| salary = \n| networth = US$5.1 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Whitney MacMillan |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/whitney-macmillan |website=Forbes |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n| term = 1977\u20131995\n| predecessor = [[Erwin Kelm]]\n| successor = [[Ernest Micek]]\n| party = \n| boards = \n| spouse = Betty MacMillan\n| children = 2\n| parents = [[Cargill MacMillan Sr|Cargill MacMillan, Sr.]]\n| relatives = [[William Wallace Cargill]] <small>(great-grandfather)</small><br/>[[Cargill MacMillan, Jr.]] <small>(brother)</small><br/>[[Pauline MacMillan Keinath]] <small>(sister)</small>\n| box_width = \n}}\n\n'''Whitney MacMillan''' (September 25, 1929 \u2013 March 11, 2020) was an American [[billionaire]] heir and businessman.<ref name=\"secretive\">Brian Solomon, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/briansolomon/2011/09/22/the-secretive-cargill-billionaires-and-their-family-tree/ The Secretive Cargill Billionaires And Their Family Tree], ''[[Forbes]]'', 9/22/2011</ref><ref name=\"hbs\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbs.edu/leadership/database/leaders/whitney_macmillan.html|title=Harvard Business School profile}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes2008\">[https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/54/400list08_Whitney-MacMillan_EKJS.html Forbes 2008: Whitney MacMillan]</ref><ref name=\"eastwest\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastwest.ngo/profile/whitney-macmillan|title=Whitney MacMillan &#124; EastWest Institute|website=www.eastwest.ngo}}</ref><ref name=\"msu\">Brenda McDonald, [http://www.montana.edu/cpa/news/nwview.php?article=174 Businessman Whitney MacMillan to receive honorary doctorate from MSU-Bozeman], Montana State University, March 26, 2002</ref> He was the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of his family business, [[Cargill]], from 1976 to 1995.<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"secretive\"/><ref name=\"hbs\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"eastwest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nWhitney MacMillan was born on September 25, 1929.<ref name=\"hbs\"/> He was the son of Pauline Whitney and [[Cargill MacMillan Sr|Cargill MacMillan, Sr.]], and the great-grandson of [[William Wallace Cargill]], the founder of [[Cargill]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"secretive\"/> He has one brother, [[Cargill MacMillan, Jr.]] (1927\u20132011), and one sister, [[Pauline MacMillan Keinath]].<ref name=\"secretive\"/><ref name=\"startribune\">Mike Hughlett, [http://www.startribune.com/local/133893083.html?refer=y Obituary: Cargill MacMillan, 84, company heir], ''[[Star Tribune|The Star Tribune]]'', November 15, 2011</ref> He graduated from [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"hbs\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Business==\nHe was CEO of Cargill from 1976 to 1995,<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/> and the last family member to be CEO.<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/> During his tenure, Cargill's annual turnover  went from $10 to $33 billion over ten years.<ref name=\"hbs\"/> By the 1980s, it became the world's largest grain company, outstripping its European rivals.<ref name=\"hbs\"/>\n\nHe was a director of the [[Western NIS Enterprise Fund]].<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"eastwest\"/> He owned and ran a cow and calf ranch in [[Park County, Montana|Park]], [[Sweet Grass County, Montana|Sweet Grass]], and [[Fergus County, Montana|Fergus]] counties in [[Montana]].<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHe served on the board of directors of the [[International Peace Institute]], the [[Salzburg Global Seminar]], the [[Landesa|Rural Development Institute]], the [[Trilateral Commission]], [[Hubert H. Humphrey School of Public Affairs]] at the [[University of Minnesota]], the [[Ruckelshaus Institute]], the [[Burton K. Wheeler Center for Public Policy]] in [[Bozeman, Montana]] and Yale University's president's council on international activities.<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref>Laurie Bennett, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/lauriebennett/2012/02/05/billionaires-welcome-on-think-tank-boards/ Billionaires Welcome on Think Tank Boards], ''Forbes'', 2/05/2012</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipinst.org/about/board-council|title=Board & Council|date=January 1, 1970}}</ref> He served on the National Advisory Board of the [[Museum of the Rockies]] in Bozeman, Montana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumoftherockies.org/AboutMOR/WhoWeAre/MORBoards.aspx|title=Museum of the Rockies National Advisory Board}}</ref> He was a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] board on agriculture and natural resources, the [[EastWest Institute]], [[CARE (relief agency)|Care International]], [[Mayo Clinic]] and the [[Council on Foreign Relations]].<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n[[The Whitney and Betty MacMillan Center for International and Area Studies at Yale]] is named for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://macmillan.yale.edu/about|title=About|website=The MacMillan Center}}</ref> In 2002, he received an honorary doctorate from [[Montana State University-Bozeman]].<ref name=\"msu\"/> He was an executive fellow and teacher at the [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]] Graduate School of Business in Minnesota.<ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\nTogether with the [[Montana Historical Society]], he was restoring the ghost town of [[Judith Landing, Montana]] at the confluence of [[Judith River]] and [[Missouri River]].<ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to Betty MacMillan. He lived in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/> As of August 2014, he was worth an estimated US$4.8 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2014/08/01/whos-rich-around-here/|title=Who\u2019s rich around here?|first=Neely|last=Tucker|date=August 1, 2014|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nHe died on March 11, 2020, in [[Vero Beach, Florida]], at the age of 90.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/whitney-macmillan-former-leader-of-cargill-and-descendant-of-its-founder-dies-at-90/568739822/|title=Whitney MacMillan, former leader of Cargill and descendant of its founder, dies at 90|website=Star Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Cargill}}\n{{Current U.S. Richest People}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macmillan, Whitney}}\n\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:Ranchers from Montana]]\n[[Category:University of St. Thomas (Minnesota) faculty]]\n[[Category:Cargill people]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Whitney MacMillan\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1929|9|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Orono, Minnesota]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|11|1929|9|25}}\n| death_place = [[Vero Beach, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = Minneapolis, Minnesota\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Yale University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman<br/>Philanthropist\n| title = CEO of [[Cargill]]\n| salary = \n| networth = US$5.1 billion (October 2019)<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Whitney MacMillan |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/whitney-macmillan |website=Forbes |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n| term = 1977\u20131995\n| predecessor = [[Erwin Kelm]]\n| successor = [[Ernest Micek]]\n| party = \n| boards = \n| spouse = Betty MacMillan\n| children = 2\n| parents = [[Cargill MacMillan Sr|Cargill MacMillan, Sr.]]\n| relatives = [[William W. Cargill]] <small>(great-grandfather)</small><br/>[[Cargill MacMillan, Jr.]] <small>(brother)</small><br/>[[Pauline MacMillan Keinath]] <small>(sister)</small>\n| box_width = \n}}\n\n'''Whitney MacMillan''' (September 25, 1929 \u2013 March 11, 2020) was an American [[billionaire]] heir and businessman.<ref name=\"secretive\">Brian Solomon, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/briansolomon/2011/09/22/the-secretive-cargill-billionaires-and-their-family-tree/ The Secretive Cargill Billionaires And Their Family Tree], ''[[Forbes]]'', 9/22/2011</ref><ref name=\"hbs\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hbs.edu/leadership/database/leaders/whitney_macmillan.html|title=Harvard Business School profile}}</ref><ref name=\"forbes2008\">[https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/54/400list08_Whitney-MacMillan_EKJS.html Forbes 2008: Whitney MacMillan]</ref><ref name=\"eastwest\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastwest.ngo/profile/whitney-macmillan|title=Whitney MacMillan &#124; EastWest Institute|website=www.eastwest.ngo}}</ref><ref name=\"msu\">Brenda McDonald, [http://www.montana.edu/cpa/news/nwview.php?article=174 Businessman Whitney MacMillan to receive honorary doctorate from MSU-Bozeman], Montana State University, March 26, 2002</ref> He was the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of his family business, [[Cargill]], from 1976 to 1995.<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"secretive\"/><ref name=\"hbs\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"eastwest\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nWhitney MacMillan was born on September 25, 1929.<ref name=\"hbs\"/> He was the son of Pauline Whitney and [[Cargill MacMillan Sr|Cargill MacMillan, Sr.]], and the great-grandson of [[William W. Cargill]], the founder of [[Cargill]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"secretive\"/> He has one brother, [[Cargill MacMillan, Jr.]] (1927\u20132011), and one sister, [[Pauline MacMillan Keinath]].<ref name=\"secretive\"/><ref name=\"startribune\">Mike Hughlett, [http://www.startribune.com/local/133893083.html?refer=y Obituary: Cargill MacMillan, 84, company heir], ''[[Star Tribune|The Star Tribune]]'', November 15, 2011</ref> He graduated from [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"hbs\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Business==\nHe was CEO of Cargill from 1976 to 1995,<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/> and the last family member to be CEO.<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/> During his tenure, Cargill's annual turnover  went from $10 to $33 billion over ten years.<ref name=\"hbs\"/> By the 1980s, it became the world's largest grain company, outstripping its European rivals.<ref name=\"hbs\"/>\n\nHe was a director of the [[Western NIS Enterprise Fund]].<ref name=\"forbes2008\"/><ref name=\"eastwest\"/> He owned and ran a cow and calf ranch in [[Park County, Montana|Park]], [[Sweet Grass County, Montana|Sweet Grass]], and [[Fergus County, Montana|Fergus]] counties in [[Montana]].<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHe served on the board of directors of the [[International Peace Institute]], the [[Salzburg Global Seminar]], the [[Landesa|Rural Development Institute]], the [[Trilateral Commission]], [[Hubert H. Humphrey School of Public Affairs]] at the [[University of Minnesota]], the [[Ruckelshaus Institute]], the [[Burton K. Wheeler Center for Public Policy]] in [[Bozeman, Montana]] and Yale University's president's council on international activities.<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref>Laurie Bennett, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/lauriebennett/2012/02/05/billionaires-welcome-on-think-tank-boards/ Billionaires Welcome on Think Tank Boards], ''Forbes'', 2/05/2012</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipinst.org/about/board-council|title=Board & Council|date=January 1, 1970}}</ref> He served on the National Advisory Board of the [[Museum of the Rockies]] in Bozeman, Montana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museumoftherockies.org/AboutMOR/WhoWeAre/MORBoards.aspx|title=Museum of the Rockies National Advisory Board}}</ref> He was a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] board on agriculture and natural resources, the [[EastWest Institute]], [[CARE (relief agency)|Care International]], [[Mayo Clinic]] and the [[Council on Foreign Relations]].<ref name=\"eastwest\"/><ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n[[The Whitney and Betty MacMillan Center for International and Area Studies at Yale]] is named for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://macmillan.yale.edu/about|title=About|website=The MacMillan Center}}</ref> In 2002, he received an honorary doctorate from [[Montana State University-Bozeman]].<ref name=\"msu\"/> He was an executive fellow and teacher at the [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]] Graduate School of Business in Minnesota.<ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\nTogether with the [[Montana Historical Society]], he was restoring the ghost town of [[Judith Landing, Montana]] at the confluence of [[Judith River]] and [[Missouri River]].<ref name=\"msu\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to Betty MacMillan. He lived in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"forbes\"/><ref name=\"forbes2008\"/> As of August 2014, he was worth an estimated US$4.8 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2014/08/01/whos-rich-around-here/|title=Who\u2019s rich around here?|first=Neely|last=Tucker|date=August 1, 2014|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nHe died on March 11, 2020, in [[Vero Beach, Florida]], at the age of 90.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/whitney-macmillan-